The Matrix was an amazing, visionary movie in its execution, but the central idea was distractingly goofy: using humans as power sources is a terrible, nonphysical idea.  I thought at the time that the movie would be much better if the machines had found that they needed some processing tasks that human brains are good at and they are not (vision and whatever underlies what we call intuition are obvious examples), and were using us for that.

Elizier Yudkowsky (http://lesswrong.com/lw/12s/the_strangest_thing_an_ai_could_tell_you), he discusses anosognosia, which is a neuroligical inability to be aware of some disability, like having a paralysed arm.

